6. Performance Evaluation

6.1 Experimental Setup

6.1.1 Test Environment

· Hardware: 16-core CPU, 64GB RAM, NVIDIA A100 GPU
· Software: Ubuntu 22.04, Python 3.9, Docker 24.0
· Algorithms: 5-20 concurrent algorithms of varying types
· Workload: Synthetic and real-world datasets

6.1.2 Evaluation Metrics

· Stability: Coherence score maintenance
· Performance: Decision accuracy and latency
· Adaptation: Intervention effectiveness and frequency
· Resource: CPU, memory, and network utilization

6.2 Results Analysis

6.2.1 Stability Improvement

Configuration Without BoA With BoA Improvement
2 Algorithms 0.78 ± 0.12 0.92 ± 0.05 +17.9%
5 Algorithms 0.65 ± 0.18 0.88 ± 0.07 +35.4%
10 Algorithms 0.52 ± 0.23 0.85 ± 0.08 +63.5%
20 Algorithms 0.41 ± 0.29 0.82 ± 0.09 +100%

6.2.2 Latency Analysis

· Processing overhead: <5ms per fusion cycle
· Adaptation latency: <50ms for stability response
· Algorithm registration: <100ms per algorithm
· Throughput: Up to 1,000 cycles/second

6.2.3 Resource Utilization

· CPU: 5-15% (scales with algorithm count)
· Memory: 100MB baseline + 1MB/algorithm
· Network: <1Mbps for telemetry and coordination

6.3 Case Study: Autonomous Vehicle Perception

6.3.1 Scenario

Coordination of 7 perception algorithms:

1. Stereo vision depth estimation
2. LiDAR point cloud processing
3. Radar object detection
4. Camera-based object classification
5. Motion prediction
6. Path planning
7. Obstacle avoidance

6.3.2 Results

· Stability improvement: From 0.61 to 0.89 coherence
· False positive reduction: 42% decrease
· Response time consistency: 23% improvement
· System uptime: From 94.2% to 99.8%

6.3.3 Safety Impact

· Critical failure prevention: 8 incidents avoided in 1000 hours
· Graceful degradation: No catastrophic failures during algorithm faults
· Recovery time: <200ms from unstable to stable state

