Appendix A: Mathematical Proofs

A.1 Stability Convergence Proof

Theorem 1: Under the BoA adaptation mechanism, system coherence $\Gamma_t$ converges to the target stability region $[\Gamma_{target}, 1]$ with probability 1.

Proof: Let $V_t = 1 - \Gamma_t$ be the instability measure. The adaptation update rule ensures:

\mathbb{E}[V_{t+1} | \mathcal{F}_t] \leq (1 - \alpha_t) V_t + \beta_t

where $\alpha_t$ represents the adaptation effectiveness and $\beta_t$ bounds the external disturbance. By the Robbins-Siegmund theorem, $V_t$ converges almost surely to a random variable $V_\infty$ satisfying:

\mathbb{E}[V_\infty] \leq \lim_{t \to \infty} \frac{\beta_t}{\alpha_t}

Given design parameters ensuring $\lim_{t \to \infty} \frac{\beta_t}{\alpha_t} \leq 1 - \Gamma_{target}$, the system converges to the stability region.

A.2 Weight Adaptation Optimality

Theorem 2: The confidence-weighted adaptation strategy achieves Pareto optimality in the trade-off between individual algorithm performance and system stability.

Proof: The adaptation strategy solves the multi-objective optimization:

\min_{\mathbf{w}} [-\sum w_i C_i, \text{Var}(\mathbf{O}), \|\Delta \mathbf{w}\|]

subject to $\sum w_i = 1, w_i \geq 0$. This forms a convex Pareto front, with the confidence-weighted strategy representing an optimal compromise point based on the weight allocation theorem.

